<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="290" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="3.[136,1452,954,1156]" pageId="3" pageNumber="290">
Diagnosis:— 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Muasya" authorityYear="2022" box="[263,416,954,975]" class="Liliopsida" family="Cyperaceae" genus="Ficinia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="3" pageNumber="290" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="stirtonii">
<emphasis box="[263,416,954,975]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="290">Ficinia stirtonii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is morphologically most similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Nees (1836: 177)" authorityName="Nees" authorityPageNumber="177" authorityYear="1836" box="[773,1077,954,976]" class="Liliopsida" family="Cyperaceae" genus="Ficinia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="3" pageNumber="290" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="argyropus">
<emphasis box="[773,896,954,975]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="290">F. argyropus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Nees von Esenbeck" box="[904,1077,954,976]" pageId="3" pageNumber="290" pagination="129 - 207" refId="ref4112" refString="Nees von Esenbeck (1836) Cyperaceae Capenses secundum novissimas Ecklonii collections. Linnaea 10: 129 - 207." type="journal article" year="1836">Nees (1836: 177)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, especially based on a common gross morphology (rhizomatous, bulbous culm base, papery white leaf sheaths) and partial overlapping of their distribution ranges. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Muasya" authorityYear="2022" class="Liliopsida" family="Cyperaceae" genus="Ficinia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="3" pageNumber="290" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="stirtonii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="290">Ficinia stirtonii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs in its shortly spicate inflorescence (vs. capitate), shape of involucral bracts auriculate (vs. linear) and glume margins entire (vs. fimbriate).
</paragraph>
